00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:02.000
So, why are we talking about our startup?

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:11.000
The reason we're talking about it is because we're often going to want to change something about the way our code behaves.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:14.000
But we don't necessarily want to change the code.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:24.000
And so, the behavior that I'm talking about there might mean, for example, I want this code to do something different depending on what computer it's running on.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:28.000
So, maybe when my code is running on my laptop, I want it to do one thing.

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:32.000
But if it's running on a server, I want it to do something else.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:38.000
And there are ways you can imagine saying, well, write an if statement.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:42.000
And if I'm on this environment, then do this.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:44.000
And if I'm on this different environment, then do that.

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:50.000
But there are better ways to do that that make your code a little bit more robust.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:57.000
And so, we'll talk about understanding how you can influence what your code does as R starts up.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:00.000
So, R startup is pretty complicated.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
There's a lot of stuff happening.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:14.000
This is a flowchart that I reference surprisingly frequently because it's helpful to understand where you have the opportunity to change the behavior of R as it starts up.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:21.000
But we're going to focus on just a couple of parts of what that setup looks like.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:27.000
So, we'll be focusing on, in particular, R environment files, which are going to enable you to set environment variables.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:37.000
And then R profile scripts, which allow you to execute little or as much R code as you want, really, as your R session is starting up.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:45.000
And we'll talk about what you need to do to create and set each of those files.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:27:02.000
So, one thing you're going to want to make sure of, just generally, and hopefully this is fixed by now, but in case it's not, you want to make sure that when you are creating one of these files, that it terminates in an empty line.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:06.000
You can configure RStudio to make sure that that happens.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:11.000
