00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:55.000
And I'm going over to code and saving and just making sure that this file ends in a new line.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:57.000
And then hitting OK.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:11.000
And so once you have that option set, then we can start thinking about modifying the R environment file or .renviron, which is fun to say five times fast.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:17.000
And so what we're going to do is we're going to use the R environment file to set environment variables.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:26.000
And the way environment variables work is there's a collection of essentially key value pairs.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:30.000
Right. So some value that has a name.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:38.000
And the point of that is that it will change the way processes behave on a computer when you start.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:46.000
So things you would want to put in an R environment file, you might want to put R specific environment variables.

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:58.000
So if you wanted to set, for example, how much history R keeps as you're executing code, you can set the R history as an environment variable.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:10.000
If you're trying to reach out to some other some other some service that provides you with data and you need an API key to connect to that service.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:17.000
So, for example, when I'm working with census data, I get an API key from the U.S. census.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:23.000
And then I use that to request data from them. And I put that as the API key in my code.

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:29.000
